    		<marginalia hand="Italian">
    			<language ident="LA">
    				<position book_orientation="90" place="left_margin">
    					<marginalia_text>
    						Vnicus mundi Orator, et pragmaticus, sempre mellitus, aut saccharatus:
    						pla[e]runq[ue] diamargaritatus, aut diamoschatus: sa[e]pè viua ambrosia,	<!-- Terms unclear.-->
    						et nectar de Coelo.
    					</marginalia_text>
    					<emphasis method="chalk" type="straight"/>
    				</position>
    			</language>
    			<translation>
    				The unique and pragmatic Orator of the world is always honey-sweet or sugar-sweet:    				
    				anointed in perals and musk: often, living ambrosia and nectar from heaven.	
    			</translation>
    		</marginalia>
    		<marginalia hand="Italian">
    			<language ident="LA">
    				<position book_orientation="90" place="left_margin">
    					<marginalia_text>
    						Et Orpheo dulcior: et lautior Proa[e]resio: et Bartasio
    						diuinior, qui superat omnes Theologos. 	
    					</marginalia_text>
    					<person name="Orpheus"/>
    					<person name="Proaeresius"/>
    					<person name="Guillaume Du Bartas"/>
    				</position>
    			</language>
    			<translation>
    				And sweeter with Orpheus: and more elegant with Proaeresius: and more divine 
    				with Barthas, who surpasses all Theologians.
    			</translation>
    		</marginalia>
    		
    		<marginalia hand="Italian">
